<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR COLLECTIBLES: CALCULATORS ARE ATTRACTING INTEREST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RONALD L. SOBLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: You've written about collecting typewriters. But is there collector 
interest in other pieces of office equipment? -- N.F. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: According to Darryl Rehr of Los Angeles, there is a "subculture of 
office equipment collectors" in this country. 
</P>
<P>
Rehr, 39, a free-lance television news journalist and typewriter collector, 
recently wrote a pamphlet, "A Beginner's Guide to Collectible Calculators," in 
which he describes calculators worth up to $1,000. (He has also written a 
similar pamphlet on typewriters.) 
</P>
<P>
"But I don't want to disillusion people," he said in a recent telephone 
conversation. "A $1,000 calculator is very, very rare." 
</P>
<P>
In the pamphlet, Rehr writes that "there are no hard-and-fast rules governing 
the collectibility of calculators, but generally speaking, today's collectors 
collect anything that is non-electronic (that is, not driven by electric 
motors)." 
</P>
<P>
To receive the pamphlet, send Rehr $1 and a self-addressed, stamped envelope, 
to 11433 Rochester Ave., 303, Los Angeles, Calif. 90025 . 
</P>
<P>
Rehr also publishes ETCetera, a quarterly newsletter on typewriters and related 
equipment. Annual subscription fee is $15. 
</P>
<P>
Of interest to car collectors will be North Hollywood auto auctioneer Rick 
Cole's sixth annual "gold list" of collector cars. Cole calls his list for 1990 
an index of the top 10 affordable automotive investment opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
Cole's list focuses on autos, currently available for under $25,000, that he 
expects to significantly appreciate in the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
Cole's current list: Austin-Healy 3000 (1960-67); Jensen Interceptor (1975-76); 
Triumph TR 2-3-4 (1953-67); MGA Roadster (1955-62); BMW 2800CS/3.0 CS Coupe 
(1971-74); Alfa Romeo Giulietta Spyder Veloce (1956-62); Chevrolet Chevelle 
(1966-72); Lotus Elan convertible (1965-68); Oldsmobile Starfire convertible 
(1961-65); and the Edsel convertible (1958-60). 
</P>
<P>
For further information, contact Rick Cole Auctions and Associates, 10701 
Riverside Drive, North Hollywood, Calif. 91602, or call (818) 506-6533. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Datebook 
</P>
<P>
An autograph and manuscript auction -- about 500 items valued at more than $1 
million -- is scheduled for May 26 at Superior Galleries, 9478 W. Olympic 
Blvd., Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Items to be auctioned include President Lyndon Johnson's executive order 
establishing the Warren Commission to investigate the Kennedy assassination; 
letters handwritten and signed by baseball pioneer Abner Doubleday; and other 
letters written by historical and literary figures. Also included will be space 
memorabilia, such as astronaut patches and the U.S. flag carried on the 1971 
Apollo 15 moon mission. Items will be priced between $100 and $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
"We're looking to make people aware that historical documents like these are 
traded like coins and stamps," said Ira Goldberg, a partner in Superior 
Galleries. "No longer are the museums and public and private libraries the only 
repositories of these historical documents." 
</P>
</TEXT>
