<P>
CENSUS RETURNS MAY FALL SHORT OF GOAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Census Bureau is now uncertain whether 70% of Americans will return their 
census forms as it had hoped, a spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
"Fifty-five percent is today's figure (for forms returned), and we're still 
hoping people will get them in," said the spokesman. On April 26, the bureau 
will send enumerators to interview members of households from which forms have 
not been received. In some cases, the enumerators will find that homes have 
been torn down or are temporarily vacant. For each percentage point below 70% 
in the response rate, the Census Bureau has estimated to Congress it will have 
to spend $10 million for extra interviewers. 
</P>
